(4/4) No matter what causes a fire to start, a properly managed forest is far more resilient than dense, overgrown woodlands. It’s common sense, and it’s time to take decisive action to help save wildlife, property, and human lives.

(3/4) Today, we witnessed two images that tell starkly contrasting stories – one that resembles a burnt out wasteland and one of a minimally damaged, healthy forest. It’s no coincidence – it’s the difference between land that is responsibly thinned, and land that is not.

(2/4) Importantly, @SecretarySonny & @SecretaryZinke are now joining me in the North State to help move the recovery process forward and make sure a tragedy like this one never happens again. pic.twitter.com/Un8gT4dPs1

(1/4) Now that the #CampFire has been 100% contained, the top priority is to help people recover. That’s why I brought President Trump to Paradise recently – so that he could see the devastation firsthand. pic.twitter.com/KgNFcVFfDn

(5/5) My office and I are in continuous discussions with the White House, DHS and FEMA on this request and are working to expedite its approval. There has been no delay and the White House has been very proactive in working with me to secure this declaration.

(4/5) On November 11, Governor Brown requested a Federal Major Disaster Declaration from President Trump.  These declarations have a great deal of paperwork and typically can take a few days to grant.

(3/5) Later on November 8th, Acting Governor Newsom requested a Presidential Emergency Declaration for Direct Assistance for Wildfires. President Trump approved the Emergency Declaration November 9th while in route to France.

(2/5) Early on November 8th, a Fire Management Assistance Grant (FMAG) was granted by (FEMA) to help ensure the availability of vital resources to suppress the Camp Fire burning in Butte County. The FMAG also enables local, state and tribal agencies to recover eligible costs.
